`event.stopPropagation()` is used to control the flow of an event through the DOM tree. It ensures that once the event reaches a certain point and `stopPropagation()` is called, it will not propagate further up (or down during capture phase) the hierarchy. It does not affect the default browser action.

questions.answer:
**Scenario 1: `event.preventDefault()` without `event.stopPropagation()`**

**Scenario:** Implementing client-side routing with an `<a>` tag that prevents a full page reload but allows the click event to bubble up to a global analytics listener.

**Explanation:**
Imagine a single-page application (SPA) where you use `<a>` tags for navigation, but instead of triggering a full page reload, you want to handle the navigation using a JavaScript router (e.g., React Router, Vue Router). In this case, you would attach a click listener to the `<a>` tag and call `event.preventDefault()` to stop the browser's default action of navigating to the `href` URL.

However, you might also have a `document`-level click listener that captures all clicks for analytics purposes (e.g., to track which links are clicked, regardless of whether they lead to an actual page reload or client-side route change). In this scenario, you *want* the event to bubble up to that global listener so that the analytics script can still record the click. Therefore, you would *not* call `event.stopPropagation()`.

```javascript
// In your routing module
const navLink = document.getElementById('myNavLink');
navLink.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
  event.preventDefault(); // Stop default navigation
  console.log('Client-side route change to:', navLink.getAttribute('href'));
  // Your routing logic here
});

// In your analytics module (listening on document)
document.addEventListener('click', function(event) {
  // This listener will still fire even if preventDefault() was called on a link
  console.log('Analytics: Click detected on:', event.target.tagName, event.target.id || event.target.className);
  // Send click data to analytics service
});
```

**Scenario 2: `event.preventDefault()` and `event.stopPropagation()` together**

**Scenario:** Creating a custom context menu (right-click menu) inside a specific area of your application, where you want to prevent the default browser context menu *and* ensure no other parent listeners are accidentally triggered.

**Explanation:**
Let's say you have a `div` element that, when right-clicked, should display a custom context menu specific to your application, instead of the browser's default context menu. You'd attach a `contextmenu` event listener to this `div`.

1.  You would call `event.preventDefault()` to stop the browser from showing its default context menu.
2.  You would also call `event.stopPropagation()` because if you have other `contextmenu` listeners on parent elements (e.g., `document.body` or `document`) that might be trying to implement their own custom context menus or perform other actions for right-clicks, you want to ensure that this specific custom context menu is the only one that appears and that no other unwanted parent listeners interfere. Stopping propagation ensures the event doesn't trigger unrelated logic higher up the DOM tree.

```javascript
// HTML:
// <div id="container" style="width: 200px; height: 100px; border: 1px solid black;">Right-click me for custom menu</div>

const container = document.getElementById('container');

container.addEventListener('contextmenu', function(event) {
  event.preventDefault();  // Stop default browser context menu
  event.stopPropagation(); // Stop event from bubbling to parent contextmenu listeners

  console.log('Displaying custom context menu!');
  // Logic to display your custom menu at event.clientX, event.clientY
});

// A global listener that should NOT be triggered for the custom menu area
document.addEventListener('contextmenu', function(event) {
  console.log('Global context menu listener triggered (should NOT happen for #container)');
});
```

