questions.example:
1.  **`orientation`**: This media feature allows you to apply styles based on whether the device is in `portrait` (height is greater than or equal to width) or `landscape` (width is greater than height) mode. For example:
    ```css
    @media (orientation: landscape) {
      .gallery-container {
        grid-template-columns: repeat(4, 1fr);
      }
    }
    ```
    This can be useful for adjusting image galleries, video layouts, or overall content flow to better fit the available screen shape, enhancing readability and visual appeal.

2.  **`prefers-color-scheme`**: This feature allows you to detect if the user has requested the system to use a light or dark color theme. It can take values `light` or `dark`. For example:
    ```css
    @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
      body {
        background-color: #333;
        color: #f0f0f0;
      }
    }
    ```
    This is crucial for providing an accessible and personalized user experience, respecting system-wide user preferences for dark mode, which can reduce eye strain in low-light conditions.

CSS nesting in Sass/SCSS allows you to write CSS selectors inside other selectors, mirroring the structure of your HTML. For example:
```scss
nav {
  ul {
    margin: 0;
    li {
      display: inline-block;
      a {
        color: blue;
      }
    }
  }
}
```

**Advantages:**
1.  **Improved Readability and Organization:** It makes the stylesheet structure more intuitive by visually representing the parent-child relationships in the DOM. Related styles are grouped together.
2.  **Reduced Repetition:** You don't have to repeatedly type parent selectors, leading to more concise code.
3.  **Encourages Modularity:** It can help group styles for specific components, making it easier to manage and move sections of CSS.

**Potential Drawbacks:**
1.  **Over-Qualified Selectors:** Excessive nesting can lead to very long and highly specific CSS selectors (e.g., `nav ul li a`). This can make it difficult to override styles later in the cascade and increases specificity conflicts.
2.  **Increased File Size:** While reducing repetition in SCSS, over-nesting might generate larger CSS files with redundant selector paths, though compilers often optimize this.
3.  **Readability Issues (if overused):** Deep nesting can make the code harder to read and navigate than a flatter structure, ironically defeating one of its primary advantages.

Best practice is to keep nesting to a minimum (typically 3-4 levels deep at most) and use it judiciously to improve organization without creating overly specific or unreadable selectors.

A Sass Mixin is perfect for this scenario. It allows you to define a block of CSS (like `border-radius` with vendor prefixes) and pass arguments (like `$radius`) to it, making it highly flexible and reusable. You would define it with `@mixin` and include it with `@include`:

```scss
@mixin border-radius($radius) {
  -webkit-border-radius: $radius;
  -moz-border-radius: $radius;
  border-radius: $radius;
}

.my-element {
  @include border-radius(5px);
}
```

Sass Variables are for storing single values. Nesting is for organizing selectors. Sass Functions return a single value and are generally used for calculations, not for injecting multiple CSS declarations.

```scss
// SCSS Code

// Variables
$base-font-size: 16px;
$primary-brand-color: #007bff;
$text-light: #fff;
$text-dark: #333;

// Mixin for a button style
@mixin button-style($bg-color: $primary-brand-color, $text-color: $text-light) {
  display: inline-block;
  padding: 10px 20px;
  border: none;
  border-radius: 5px;
  background-color: $bg-color;
  color: $text-color;
  font-size: $base-font-size;
  cursor: pointer;
  text-decoration: none;
  text-align: center;
  transition: background-color 0.3s ease;

  &:hover {
    opacity: 0.9;
  }
}

// Nesting for header, nav, ul, li
header {
  background-color: #f8f9fa;
  padding: 15px 0;
  border-bottom: 1px solid #e9ecef;
  text-align: center;

  nav {
    max-width: 960px;
    margin: 0 auto;

    ul {
      list-style: none;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      display: flex;
      justify-content: center;
      gap: 20px;

      li {
        a {
          color: $text-dark;
          text-decoration: none;
          font-weight: bold;
          font-size: $base-font-size;

          &:hover {
            color: $primary-brand-color;
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }

  .cta-button {
    margin-top: 20px;
    @include button-style($primary-brand-color, $text-light); // Applying the mixin
  }
}

// Example of another button type using the mixin with different arguments
.secondary-button {
  @include button-style(#6c757d, $text-light);
}

```

