theory.content:
Vue.js applications are composed of reusable components. A Vue component typically consists of three main blocks: `<template>`, `<script>`, and `<style>` (not shown in the example, but common).

### Single File Components (SFCs)
Vue often uses Single File Components (SFCs) with a `.vue` extension. These files encapsulate the component's template, logic, and styles in a single, cohesive file.

*   **`<template>`**: Contains the HTML structure of the component's view. It must have a single root element.
*   **`<script>`**: Contains the component's JavaScript logic. When using the Options API (as in the example), `export default` is used to define the component's options.
    *   **`data()`**: A function that returns an object containing the reactive data for the component. Each property in this object will become reactive, meaning Vue will track its changes and update the view accordingly.
    *   **`methods`**: An object containing methods (functions) that can be called from the template (e.g., in response to user events).
*   **`<style>` (Optional)**: Contains the CSS for the component. Can be scoped to prevent styles from leaking to other components.

### Data Reactivity and Event Handling
Vue's reactivity system automatically tracks changes to data properties and efficiently updates the DOM. Event handling in Vue templates uses the `v-on` directive, often shortened to `@`. For example, `@click="methodName"` binds a click event to a method defined in the `methods` option.

#### Basic Usage
```html
<template>
  <div>
    <p>{{ message }}</p>
    <button @click="changeMessage">Change Message</button>
  </div>
</template>

<script>
export default {
  data() {
    return {
      message: 'Hello Vue!'
    };
  },
  methods: {
    changeMessage() {
      this.message = 'Message Changed!';
    }
  }
};
</script>
```

