tasks.description:
Your task is to optimize the CSS delivery for a simple blog post page. The goal is to ensure the 'above-the-fold' content (header, main title, and initial paragraph) renders as quickly as possible by inlining its critical CSS, while the rest of the styles are loaded asynchronously.

**Requirements:**
1.  Identify the critical CSS for the `header`, `h1` (post title), and the first `p` (introduction).
2.  Inline this critical CSS directly into a `<style>` block within the `<head>` section of the HTML document.
3.  Ensure the main `styles.css` file (containing all other styles) is loaded asynchronously using `rel="preload"`, `as="style"`, and the `onload` trick.
4.  Include a `noscript` fallback for `styles.css`.
5.  Add some non-critical styles to `styles.css` that would apply to 'below-the-fold' content (e.g., footer, sidebars, or subsequent paragraphs).

**Assumed Critical Styles:**
```css
body { font-family: sans-serif; margin: 0; line-height: 1.6; color: #333; }
header { background: #f4f4f4; padding: 20px; text-align: center; border-bottom: 1px solid #ccc; }
h1 { color: #2c3e50; font-size: 2.5em; margin-bottom: 10px; }
.post-intro { font-size: 1.1em; color: #555; }
```

**Assumed Non-Critical Styles (for `styles.css`):**
```css
.post-content { padding: 20px; max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto; }
.post-content p { margin-bottom: 1em; }
footer { background: #eee; padding: 10px; text-align: center; margin-top: 40px; }
.sidebar { width: 200px; float: right; margin-left: 20px; }
```

