```typescript
import React, { useState, useCallback, useMemo } from 'react';

const ChildComponent = React.memo(({ onClick, value }) => {
  console.log('ChildComponent re-rendered');
  return <button onClick={onClick}>Child Button: {value}</button>;
});

function ParentComponent() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  const [text, setText] = useState('Hello');

  // Scenario for useCallback: Passing a stable callback to a memoized child
  const handleChildClick = useCallback(() => {
    setCount(prev => prev + 1);
  }, []); // Empty dependency array means this function reference is stable

  // Example for useMemo: Expensive calculation
  const expensiveValue = useMemo(() => {
    console.log('Calculating expensive value...');
    let sum = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < 10000000; i++) {
      sum += i;
    }
    return sum + count; // Recalculates if count changes
  }, [count]);

  return (
    <div>
      <p>Parent Count: {count}</p>
      <p>Parent Text: {text}</p>
      <p>Expensive Value: {expensiveValue}</p>
      <ChildComponent onClick={handleChildClick} value={count} />
      <button onClick={() => setText(text + '!')}>Change Parent Text (Forces Parent Re-render)</button>
    </div>
  );
}
```
In `ParentComponent`, if `setText` is called, `ParentComponent` re-renders. Without `useCallback` for `handleChildClick`, a *new* function reference would be created on each render. Even though the *logic* of `handleChildClick` hasn't changed, its reference would. Since `ChildComponent` is `React.memo`-ized, it performs a shallow prop comparison. A new function reference for `onClick` would cause `ChildComponent` to re-render unnecessarily. `useCallback` prevents this by returning the same function reference unless its dependencies change.

