tasks.solutionCode:
function fibonacciMemoized(n) {
  const memo = {}; // Cache to store computed Fibonacci numbers

  function fib(num) {
    if (num in memo) { // Check if result is already in cache
      return memo[num];
    }

    if (num < 2) { // Base cases
      return num;
    }

    // Compute, store in cache, and return
    memo[num] = fib(num - 1) + fib(num - 2);
    return memo[num];
  }

  return fib(n);
}

/*
Analysis:
Time Complexity: O(n)
Each Fibonacci number from 0 to n is computed only once. Although it's recursive, the memoization ensures that for each 'num', the 'fib' function is called exactly once to compute its value and store it. Subsequent calls retrieve the value directly from the memo.

Space Complexity: O(n)
This is due to two factors:
1. The 'memo' object stores up to 'n' key-value pairs.
2. The recursion call stack can go up to 'n' levels deep in the worst case (e.g., for fib(n), it will call fib(n-1), then fib(n-2) etc. until fib(1) or fib(0) is hit on one branch, before returning and exploring the other branch).
*/

