theory.content:
To integrate Redux with React applications, the `react-redux` library is typically used. It provides bindings that allow your React components to read data from the Redux store and dispatch actions to it, abstracting away the direct interaction with `store.subscribe()` and `store.dispatch()`.

## Providing the Store

The first step is to make the Redux store available to your React component tree. This is done using the `<Provider>` component from `react-redux` at the root of your application:

```tsx
import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';
import { Provider } from 'react-redux';
import { store } from './app/store'; // Your Redux store
import App from './App';

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root') as HTMLElement);
root.render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <Provider store={store}>
      <App />
    </Provider>
  </React.StrictMode>
);
```

## Connecting Components (Class Components)

For class components, `react-redux` provides the `connect` higher-order component (HOC). `connect` is a function that takes two optional arguments, `mapStateToProps` and `mapDispatchToProps`, and returns a new function. This new function then takes your React component and returns a 'connected' component.

```tsx
import React from 'react';
import { connect } from 'react-redux';
import { addTodo, toggleTodo } from './actions'; // Action creators

class TodoApp extends React.Component<{ todos: any[], addTodo: (text: string) => void, toggleTodo: (index: number) => void }> {
  render() {
    return (
      <div>
        <h1>Todos</h1>
        <input 
          type="text" 
          onKeyPress={(e) => {
            if (e.key === 'Enter') {
              this.props.addTodo((e.target as HTMLInputElement).value);
              (e.target as HTMLInputElement).value = '';
            }
          }}
          placeholder="Add a new todo"
        />
        <ul>
          {this.props.todos.map((todo, index) => (
            <li key={index} onClick={() => this.props.toggleTodo(index)}>
              {todo.text} {todo.completed ? '(Completed)' : ''}
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      </div>
    );
  }
}

// mapStateToProps: Defines which parts of the Redux state your component needs
const mapStateToProps = (state: any) => ({ 
  todos: state.todos // Assuming your root state has a 'todos' slice
});

// mapDispatchToProps: Defines which actions your component can dispatch
// Option 1: Manual mapping - Most verbose, offers full control over dispatch logic.
//           Useful if you need to transform dispatch props or perform side effects.
const mapDispatchToPropsOption1 = (dispatch: any) => ({
  addTodo: (text: string) => dispatch(addTodo(text)),
  toggleTodo: (index: number) => dispatch(toggleTodo(index)),
  // You can also add custom dispatch logic here
  logAction: (actionType: string) => {
    console.log(`Action dispatched: ${actionType}`);
    dispatch({ type: actionType });
  }
});

// Option 2: Object shorthand - The most common and concise way.
//           If an action creator is passed as a value, `connect` automatically wraps it in `dispatch`.
const mapDispatchToPropsOption2 = {
  addTodo,   // Equivalent to (text) => dispatch(addTodo(text))
  toggleTodo // Equivalent to (index) => dispatch(toggleTodo(index))
};

// Connect the component to Redux
// You can choose either mapDispatchToPropsOption1 or mapDispatchToPropsOption2
export default connect(mapStateToProps, mapDispatchToPropsOption2)(TodoApp);
```

## Connecting Components (Functional Components with Hooks)

For functional components, `react-redux` provides hooks (`useSelector` and `useDispatch`), which are the recommended approach for new applications. They offer a simpler and more direct way to interact with the store.

```tsx
import React from 'react';
import { useSelector, useDispatch } from 'react-redux';
import { addTodo, toggleTodo } from './actions'; // Action creators

interface Todo { text: string; completed: boolean; }
interface RootState { todos: Todo[]; }

function FunctionalTodoApp() {
  // useSelector: Extracts data from the Redux store state
  const todos = useSelector((state: RootState) => state.todos);

  // useDispatch: Returns a reference to the store's dispatch function
  const dispatch = useDispatch();

  const handleAddTodo = (e: React.KeyboardEvent<HTMLInputElement>) => {
    if (e.key === 'Enter') {
      dispatch(addTodo((e.target as HTMLInputElement).value));
      (e.target as HTMLInputElement).value = '';
    }
  };

  const handleToggleTodo = (index: number) => {
    dispatch(toggleTodo(index));
  };

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>Functional Todos</h1>
      <input 
        type="text" 
        onKeyPress={handleAddTodo}
        placeholder="Add a new todo"
      />
      <ul>
        {todos.map((todo, index) => (
          <li key={index} onClick={() => handleToggleTodo(index)}>
            {todo.text} {todo.completed ? '(Completed)' : ''}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  );
}

export default FunctionalTodoApp;
```

### `useSelector` vs `mapStateToProps`
-   `useSelector` allows you to directly select a slice of state in your functional component. It automatically subscribes to the Redux store and re-renders the component when the selected state changes. It takes a selector function as its argument.
-   `mapStateToProps` is a function that maps parts of the Redux state to component props for class components. It returns an object that gets merged into the component's props.

### `useDispatch` vs `mapDispatchToProps`
-   `useDispatch` returns a reference to the `dispatch` function from the Redux store. You can then call `dispatch(actionCreator(args))` directly within your functional component.
-   `mapDispatchToProps` maps action creators to component props for class components. It can be an object (shorthand for binding action creators) or a function that receives `dispatch` as an argument.

